      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "act": "ALGEBRA",
      "narration_text": "The ladder construction allows j equal to zero, one half, one, three halves, and so on. Nothing in those commutation relations alone selects only integers.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.92,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:32:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "act": "PUZZLE",
      "narration_text": "Atomic orbitals have ell equal to zero, one, two, and three: s, p, d, and f. Intrinsic electron spin has j equal to one half. Same angular-momentum algebra, different realization.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.84,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:32:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "act": "QUESTION",
      "narration_text": "Why does the orbital problem discard the algebra's half-integer options while intrinsic spin keeps them? The missing ingredient is the space on which rotations act.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.83,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:32:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "act": "NAIVE",
      "narration_text": "A naive reading stops at the algebra and predicts half-integer orbitals. But solving the orbital problem adds spatial boundary conditions that the abstract algebra never contained.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.05,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:32:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "act": "ORBITAL CONDITION",
      "narration_text": "For the azimuthal factor of a scalar orbital wavefunction, exp i m phi must agree when phi advances by two pi. That requires exp two pi i m equal one, so m is an integer.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 14,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.82,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:32:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "act": "FAILED HALF",
      "narration_text": "Try m equal one half in that scalar orbital factor. After phi advances by two pi, the factor changes sign. It fails the single-valued orbital boundary condition.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.73,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:32:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "act": "SPIN SPACE",
      "narration_text": "Intrinsic spin is an internal spinor degree of freedom, not scalar orbital dependence on the azimuthal coordinate. Spinors can change sign under a two-pi rotation while representing the same physical ray; relative signs remain observable in interference.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 15,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 15.15,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:32:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "act": "IMPLICATION",
      "narration_text": "So integer-only orbital ell comes from the spatial representation and its boundary conditions. Half-integer spin comes from a different representation of rotations. The algebra accommodates both.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.82,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:32:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "act": "CAVEAT",
      "narration_text": "A particle with spin can still have a position-space wavefunction: it is spinor-valued, with internal components at every position. The accurate claim is not that spin has no position space, but that it is not orbital motion around phi.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 15,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.76,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:32:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "act": "RECAP",
      "narration_text": "Algebra permits integer and half-integer j. Scalar orbital boundary conditions select integer ell. Intrinsic spin uses spinor representations, where a two-pi sign change is allowed.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.52,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:32:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "act": "YOUR TURN",
      "narration_text": "Your turn. Evaluate exp two pi i m. For m equal one, the answer is plus one. For m equal one half, it is minus one. Which satisfies the scalar orbital boundary condition? Only the integer.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 15,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.07,
